com.android.dialogs

Class ScrollViewDialog

  • java.lang.Object
    • DialogFragment
      • com.android.dialogs.AlertDialogs
        • com.android.dialogs.ScrollViewDialog
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    PreferencesDialog, ScrollViewSwitchDialog, WelcomeDialogCheckRequirements_1Step, WelcomeDialogCheckRequirements_2Step, WelcomeDialogCheckRequirements_3Step

    public class ScrollViewDialog
extends AlertDialogs
    Displays the alert dialog box that contains ScrollView. Dialog box, extending the class of AlertDialogs. Instead of plain text, the contents of the dialog box (except the title, icon, buttons that was already defined in super class) is defined in a different, specially defined ScrollView (see {@link ScrollViewDialog#VIEW_ID).

      • buildDialogContent

        public void buildDialogContent(Builder builder)
        Adds dialogInnerView to dialog box. Overrides a part of AlertDialogs.onCreateDialog(Bundle) that is responsible for building a main part of the dialog. Instead of simple message, the entire new ScrollView will be added, based on value:
        • VIEW_ID
        that was created in newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer). ID value that this method needs is stored in the key-value pair <VIEW_ID,X>, where X is that value.
        Overrides:
        buildDialogContent in class AlertDialogs
        Parameters:
        builder - AlertDialogs.dialogBuilder that builds entire dialog window

      • showDialog

        public static void showDialog(Activity activity,
              java.lang.String dialogIDTag,
              java.lang.Integer titleIconID,
              java.lang.Integer titleID,
              ScrollView view,
              java.lang.Integer positiveButtonID,
              java.lang.Integer neutralButtonID,
              java.lang.Integer negativeButtonID)
        Displays alert dialog in given Activity. Usage example: 
         ScrollViewDialog.showDialog(this,
                                        ConnectionsActivity.DialogList.TAG_CONNECT_CONFIRMATION,
                                        ConnectionsActivity.DialogList.ID_TITLE_ICON_WIFI,
                                        ConnectionsActivity.DialogList.ID_TITLE_CONNECT_CONFIRMATION,
                                        ScrollViewDialog.getViewFromResource(this,R.layout.dialog_check_requirements),
                                        DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_CONNECT,
                                        null,
                                        DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_CANCEL);
        In the above code in this Activity dialog box is displayed, which is containing 2 of 3 buttons:
        • Positive button with label defined under DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_OPTIONS,
        • Negative button with label defined under DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_CANCEL.
        Neutral button will not be even displayed as null value is set. View can be set either by passing:
        • layout ID which contains ScrollView as a root element (see getViewFromResource(Activity, int)),
        • view ID by Activity#findViewById(int).
        Parameters:
        activity - activity where dialog will be displayed
        dialogIDTag - a unique value to distinguish dialog boxes where more than one is displayed in one activity
        titleIconID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        titleID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        view - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        positiveButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        neutralButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        negativeButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, ScrollView, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters

      • dialogInnerViewLogic

        public void dialogInnerViewLogic()
        Defines entire logic for custom ScrollView added to the dialog. Base logic is to initialize returnedData to store returned data. Extra logic commonly will consist of:
        • searching a view by Activity#findViewById(int)
        • setting a tag for the found view (and key for returnedData)
        • adding additional listeners to the view e.g.
          • OnCheckedChangeListener
          • TextWatcher
          • OnSeekBarChangeListener
        • setting default values for a key-value pair.
        See example: AddConnectionDialog.dialogInnerViewLogic().
